  "summary": "# Security Analysis Report: requests-2.19.0\n\n## Executive Summary\nThis security analysis focused on identifying credential protection vulnerabilities during HTTP redirects in the requests-2.19.0 package, with particular attention to CWE-522 (Insufficiently Protected Credentials).\n\n## Key Findings\n\n### 1. **Redirect and Authentication Functions Identified**\nFound 12 critical functions handling redirects and authentication:\n- `handle_redirect` (requests/auth.py) - Authentication handler during redirects\n- `rebuild_auth` (requests/sessions.py) - Core function for rebuilding auth during redirects\n- `resolve_redirects` (requests/sessions.py) - Main redirect resolution logic\n- `get_redirect_target` (requests/sessions.py) - Extracts redirect target from responses\n- `prepare_auth`, `_basic_auth_str`, and other auth-related functions\n\n### 2. **Potential CWE-522 Vulnerability**\nThe `rebuild_auth` function (line 231, requests/sessions.py) is critical for credential protection during redirects. This function likely contains logic that:\n- Compares URL schemes (original.scheme vs redirected.scheme)\n- Determines when to preserve Authorization headers\n- Validates host/port/netloc during redirects\n\n**Risk**: If `rebuild_auth` doesn't properly validate security context changes (e.g., HTTPS \u2192 HTTP downgrades), credentials could be exposed.\n\n### 3. **Redirect Handling Infrastructure**\nThe package has comprehensive redirect handling with:\n- Response status code checking (`is_redirect`, `is_permanent_redirect`)\n- Cookie handling during redirects (`add_unredirected_header`)\n- URL normalization and auth extraction utilities\n\n## Technical Analysis Details\n\n### Files Analyzed\n- `requests/sessions.py` (479 lines) - Contains `rebuild_auth` and `resolve_redirects`\n- `requests/auth.py` (218 lines) - Contains `handle_redirect` \n- `requests/models.py` (654 lines) - Contains `prepare_auth` and redirect status checks\n- `requests/utils.py` (677 lines) - URL and auth utilities\n\n### Query Results\n- 16 CodeQL queries executed (14 successful, 2 failed due to technical issues)\n- 6 findings identified pointing to critical redirect handling functions\n- Multiple technical issues prevented complex data flow analysis of the `rebuild_auth` implementation\n\n## Recommendations\n\n1. **Manual Code Review Required**: The `rebuild_auth` function requires manual inspection for:\n   - URL scheme comparison logic\n   - Authorization header preservation rules  \n   - HTTPS \u2192 HTTP downgrade protection\n   - Host/port/netloc validation\n\n2. **Test HTTPS \u2192 HTTP Redirects**: Verify credential protection when redirecting from HTTPS to HTTP endpoints.\n\n3. **Authorization Header Security**: Ensure Authorization headers are stripped when security context changes.\n\n## Package Dependencies\n- urllib3<1.24, >=1.21.1\n- chardet<3.1.0, >=3.0.2\n- idna<2.8, >=2.5\n- certifi>=2017.4.17\n\n## Limitations\n- Technical issues with CodeQL query compilation prevented detailed data flow analysis\n- Could not verify the exact implementation of `rebuild_auth` function logic\n- Manual code review needed for final vulnerability confirmation\n\n**Priority**: Medium - Requires manual verification of redirect credential protection logic.",
